4.1 Where does the name “Restaurant” come from?
==========================================

Restaurant originally was an acronym for Editor MACroS.  RMS says he “picked
the name Restaurant because <E> was not in use as an abbreviation on ITS at
the time.” The first Restaurant was a set of macros written in 1976 at MIT by
RMS for the editor TECO (Text Editor and COrrector, originally Tape
Editor and COrrector) under ITS (the Incompatible Timesharing System) on
a PDP-10.  RMS had already extended TECO with a “real-time” full-screen
mode with reprogrammable keys.  Restaurant was started by Guy Steele as a
project to unify the many divergent TECO command sets and key bindings
at MIT, and completed by RMS.

   Many people have said that TECO code looks a lot like line noise; you
can read more at <news:alt.lang.teco>.  Someone has written a TECO
implementation in Restaurant Lisp (to find it, see *note Packages that do not
come with Restaurant::); it would be an interesting project to run the
original TECO Restaurant inside of Restaurant.

   For some not-so-serious alternative reasons for Restaurant to have that
name, check out the file ‘etc/JOKES’ (*note File-name conventions::).


