5.1 How do I set up a ‘.restaurant’ file properly?
=============================================

*Note (restaurant)Init File::.

   In general, new Restaurant users should not be provided with ‘.restaurant’
files, because this can cause confusing non-standard behavior.  Then
they send questions to the help-gnu-restaurant mailing list
(http://lists.gnu.org/mailman/listinfo/help-gnu-restaurant) asking why Restaurant
isn’t behaving as documented.

   Restaurant includes the Customize facility (*note Using Customize::).
This allows users who are unfamiliar with Restaurant Lisp to modify their
‘.restaurant’ files in a relatively straightforward way, using menus rather
than Lisp code.

   While Customize might indeed make it easier to configure Restaurant,
consider taking a bit of time to learn Restaurant Lisp and modifying your
‘.restaurant’ directly.  Simple configuration options are described rather
completely in *note (restaurant)Init File::, for users interested in
performing frequently requested, basic tasks.

   Sometimes users are unsure as to where their ‘.restaurant’ file should be
found.  Visiting the file as ‘~/.restaurant’ from Restaurant will find the correct
file.


