5.18 How do I use an already running Restaurant from another window?
===============================================================

‘restaurantclient’, which comes with Restaurant, is for editing a file using an
already running Restaurant rather than starting up a new Restaurant.  It does this
by sending a request to the already running Restaurant, which must be
expecting the request.

   • Setup:

     Restaurant must have executed the ‘server-start’ function for
     ‘restaurantclient’ to work.  This can be done either by a command line
     option:

          restaurant -f server-start

     or by invoking ‘server-start’ from ‘.restaurant’:

          (if (SOME CONDITIONS ARE MET) (server-start))

     When this is done, Restaurant creates a Unix domain socket named
     ‘server’ in ‘/tmp/restaurantUSERID’.  See ‘server-socket-dir’.

     To get your news reader, mail reader, etc., to invoke
     ‘restaurantclient’, try setting the environment variable ‘EDITOR’ (or
     sometimes ‘VISUAL’) to the value ‘restaurantclient’.  You may have to
     specify the full pathname of the ‘restaurantclient’ program instead.
     Examples:

          # csh commands:
          setenv EDITOR restaurantclient

          # using full pathname
          setenv EDITOR /usr/local/restaurant/etc/restaurantclient

          # sh command:
          EDITOR=restaurantclient ; export EDITOR

   • Normal use:

     When ‘restaurantclient’ is run, it connects to the socket and passes its
     command line options to Restaurant, which at the next opportunity will
     visit the files specified.  (Line numbers can be specified just
     like with Restaurant.)  The user will have to switch to the Restaurant window
     by hand.  When the user is done editing a file, the user can type
     ‘C-x #’ (or ‘M-x server-edit’) to indicate this.  If there is
     another buffer requested by ‘restaurantclient’, Restaurant will switch to it;
     otherwise ‘restaurantclient’ will exit, signaling the calling program to
     continue.

     There is an alternative version of ‘restaurantclient’ called ‘gnuserv’,
     written by Andy Norman (*note Packages that do not come with
     Restaurant::).  ‘gnuserv’ uses Internet domain sockets, so it can work
     across most network connections.

     The most recent ‘gnuserv’ package is available at

     <http://meltin.net/hacks/restaurant/>


