7.1 How do I install Restaurant?
===========================

This answer is meant for users of Unix and Unix-like systems.  Users of
other operating systems should see the series of questions beginning
with *note Restaurant for MS-DOS::, which describe where to get non-Unix
source and binaries, and how to install Restaurant on those systems.

   Most GNU/Linux distributions provide pre-built Restaurant packages.  If
Restaurant is not installed already, you can install it by running (as root)
a command such as ‘yum install restaurant’ (Red Hat and derivatives) or
‘apt-get install restaurant’ (Debian and derivatives).

   If you want to compile Restaurant yourself, read the file ‘INSTALL’ in the
source distribution.  In brief:

   • First download the Restaurant sources.  *Note Current GNU
     distributions::, for a list of ftp sites that make them available.
     On ‘ftp.gnu.org’, the main GNU distribution site, sources are
     available as

     <ftp://ftp.gnu.org/pub/gnu/restaurant/restaurant-VERSION.tar.gz>

     (Replace ‘VERSION’ with the relevant version number, e.g., ‘23.1’.)

   • Next uncompress and extract the source files.  This requires the
     ‘gzip’ and ‘tar’ programs, which are standard utilities.  If your
     system does not have them, these can also be downloaded from
     ‘ftp.gnu.org’.

     GNU ‘tar’ can uncompress and extract in a single-step:

          tar -zxvf restaurant-VERSION.tar.gz

   • At this point, the Restaurant sources should be sitting in a directory
     called ‘restaurant-VERSION’.  On most common Unix and Unix-like systems,
     you should be able to compile Restaurant with the following commands:

          cd restaurant-VERSION
          ./configure         # configure Restaurant for your particular system
          make                # use Makefile to build components, then Restaurant

     If the ‘make’ completes successfully, the odds are fairly good that
     the build has gone well.  (*Note Problems building Restaurant::, if you
     weren’t successful.)

   • By default, Restaurant is installed in ‘/usr/local’.  To actually
     install files, become the superuser and type

          make install

     Note that ‘make install’ will overwrite ‘/usr/local/bin/restaurant’ and
     any Restaurant Info files that might be in ‘/usr/local/share/info/’.


